Normalized and Scaling the Data

  • Normalized the data

  • Identification of highly variable features (feature selection)

By directly modeling the mean-variance relationship inherent in single-cell data, and is implemented in the FindVariableFeatures() function. By default, we return 2,000 features per dataset. These will be used in downstream analysis, like PCA.

  • Scaling the Data

Shifts the expression of each gene, so that the mean expression across cells is 0.

Scales the expression of each gene, so that the variance across cells is 1.

This step gives equal weight in downstream analyses, so that highly-expressed genes do not dominate.

The results of this are stored in pbmc[[RNA]]@scale.data.

#GF1APCP
GF1APCP <- NormalizeData(GF1APCP)
GF1APCP <- FindVariableFeatures(GF1APCP, selection.method = "mean.var.plot")
GF1APCP <- ScaleData(GF1APCP, features = VariableFeatures(GF1APCP))
## Centering and scaling data matrix
#GF2RB1P
GF2RB1P <- NormalizeData(GF2RB1P)
GF2RB1P <- FindVariableFeatures(GF2RB1P, selection.method = "mean.var.plot")
GF2RB1P <- ScaleData(GF2RB1P, features = VariableFeatures(GF2RB1P))
## Centering and scaling data matrix
#GF2RBM10P
GF2RBM10P <- NormalizeData(GF2RBM10P)
GF2RBM10P <- FindVariableFeatures(GF2RBM10P, selection.method = "mean.var.plot")
GF2RBM10P <- ScaleData(GF2RBM10P, features = VariableFeatures(GF2RBM10P))
## Centering and scaling data matrix
#GF3kEAP1P
GF3kEAP1P <- NormalizeData(GF3kEAP1P)
GF3kEAP1P <- FindVariableFeatures(GF3kEAP1P, selection.method = "mean.var.plot")

Adding HTO data as an independent assay

  • Add HTO data as a new assay independent from RNA

  • Normalize HTO data, here we use centered log-ratio (CLR) transformation

# GF1APCP
GF1APCP[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF1APCP_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF1APCP)])
GF1APCP <- NormalizeData(GF1APCP, assay = "HTO", normalization.method = "CLR")
## Normalizing across features
# GF2RB1P
GF2RB1P[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF2RB1P_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF2RB1P)])
GF2RB1P <- NormalizeData(GF2RB1P, assay = "HTO", normalization.method = "CLR")
## Normalizing across features
# GF2RBM10P
GF2RBM10P[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF2RBM10P_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF2RBM10P)])
GF2RBM10P <- NormalizeData(GF2RBM10P, assay = "HTO", normalization.method = "CLR")
## Normalizing across features
# GF3kEAP1P
GF3kEAP1P[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF3kEAP1P_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF3kEAP1P)])
GF3kEAP1P <- NormalizeData(GF3kEAP1P, assay = "HTO", normalization.method = "CLR")
## Normalizing across features
# GF4_Neo2_P
GF4_Neo2_P[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF4_Neo2_P_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF4_Neo2_P)])
GF4_Neo2_P <- NormalizeData(GF4_Neo2_P, assay = "HTO", normalization.method = "CLR")
## Normalizing across features
# GF4_Smad4_P
GF4_Smad4_P[["HTO"]] <- CreateAssayObject(counts = GF4_Smad4_P_data$`Antibody Capture`[,colnames(GF4_Smad4_P)])
